metadata.name: Unsolicited abstraction of modern times #174
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?  

Inspired by textbooks of the 80s, with elements that remind us of industry, technology, networks and systems, "Unsolicited abstraction of modern times" invites us to question our work to date. Has everything really changed?

unknowable 2022




Usage:
press [s] - save pixels (png)
press [p] - save vectors (svg)

metadata.name: Concrete #156
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: A Slight Case of Overbombing #16
metadata.description:
Inspired by monochromatic art of the late 60s, Russian folk-art woodblock prints, and the stylised colours of British underground comics, excited to introduce a series of bold rich landscapes. England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland represented by red, yellow, green and blue, sometimes a house or two, and groovy clouds.

Instructions ::

.     - speed up
,     - slow down
space - pause
n     - toggle noise
p     - cycle palette
h     - toggle high-res (and definitely intentional pixel shift)
s     - download and save image

metadata.name: ChromaSlide #82
metadata.description:
ChromaSlide generates animations that fill the screen, run forever, and do not repeat.

Most editions have a 4 color palette and each color emerges only from one of the edges. Dashed lines are drawn at an edge and then the pixels in a rectangular region are shifted. The overlap between different regions cause a mixing and complex movement of the colored pixels. Will the color that emerges from one side reach the opposite or get shunted aside? Does one color dominate over the others? Do persistent structures emerge from the sliding colors?

--------------------------

This is a 100% code generated project.

Click on the output to stop and start the animation.
Use the 's' key to save the current frame.

Copyright 2024 Jeff Clark
--------------------------

All drawing and geometric code created by Jeff Clark using standard javascript and canvas 2D api.

metadata.name: Aurora At Mount St. Matrice #36
metadata.description:
At the gateway of waking and sleep, warmed by a molten heart; into the arms of night - be bathed by her falling hair.

Process: Forged in Hydra.

🌐 A note on rarity and variety: 

Although there are many variations possible within this piece, they are on the subtler side.

As this is a highly temporal piece, these variations ask you to dive into the experience of the piece in order to fully appreciate them. Please proceed bearing this in mind.

Experiment with the aspect ratio of this piece using the ‘open live’ function below the viewport - it can be enjoyed elastically [as with my previous works here]. A larger frame provides for a deeper experience.

As with a handful of my works, an instance of .blend() is used in this piece, and does cause some slight thinning and dimming to the preview capture. Once more, this still preview is to be considered a skeletal scan of a moment within this piece.

metadata.name: CA Panico #79
metadata.description:
Third chapter of the trilogy dedicated to Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.
 
Compared to CA Vista and CA Monti, CA Panico aims to further abstract the concept of landscape using CA rules in a more massive way.

The great variety of CA rules that controls the coloring and textures, noise influence, division into quadrants, chance of having glitches and outages all combined with 25 palettes and 5 different formats means that the outputs will be very varied and peculiar.

Press 'S' to download, you can zoom downloaded output to enjoy all the details.

metadata.name: CA Monti #220
metadata.description:
